# Prefer groupBy Over Multiple Filters

When splitting the same array into buckets by a property, use **`Object.groupBy`** once instead of multiple **`.filter`** passes.

## Rules

- One pass over the data, not N filters for N buckets.
- Use a callback that returns a stable string key (or symbol) per bucket.
- Missing keys are `undefined` — default to `[]` when destructuring arrays.

## Example

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — two full scans
const customerFindings = findings.filter((finding) => !finding.awsManaged);
const awsManagedFindings = findings.filter((finding) => finding.awsManaged);

// ✅ GOOD — single pass
const { managed = [], unmanaged = [] } = Object.groupBy(
  findings,
  (finding) => (finding.awsManaged ? "managed" : "unmanaged"),
);
```

Keep the grouped object when callers need a map keyed by category:

```typescript
const checksByEvidence = Object.groupBy(checks, (check) => check.evidenceKey);
```

## When filter is still fine

- A single exclusion or inclusion with no sibling buckets.
- Filtering after grouping, or on a different source array than the partition.
